Ball handling isn't where you would like it to be just yet but the vision is definitely there for Earl Timberlake https://t.co/gsO9kKQTQI

DeMatha often trusted him to mark up against the opposing team's most talented player, which included the much quicker Jeremy Roach. Here he's able to keep Roach on his hips and block his layup without fouling https://t.co/0nsOuTeFZm
Can play a multitude of positions, and shows good patience down low. Here he directs the passing of the guards, before making a smooth backdoor spin and drawing the foul https://t.co/f4Zilmf3gW

An underrated aspect of Timberlake's game is his vision. Brings the ball up the court a lot for DeMatha which allows him to see tight angles and throw pinpoint passes like this one, which totally broke down the defense https://t.co/oy4qmACMTd

Not a great rebounder, but is willing to use his strength to get good inside positioning on a taller player, and his tenacious hustle allows him to outwork the other man for the board https://t.co/W3uA8cw9Ah

Timberlake's plus athleticism allows him to recover from a missed shot, chase down a much smaller and quicker guard (Duke commit Jeremy Roach), pin his shot off the glass, then quickly recover to contest the follow up attempt https://t.co/z9PAG3oclX

One of my favorite under-the-radar 2021 prospects, here's a thread of Miami bound Earl Timberlake, a 6'6" strong slasher and defender. Here's the lefty driving past a taller defender for the transition finish in traffic https://t.co/Res8qhx6fB

Guys I had in draftable range who declared and are returning:

Jared Butler, Aaron Henry, Joel Ayayi, Ayo Dosunmu, Isaiah Joe, Herb Jones, JRE, Joe Weiskamp, Luka Garza, Derrick Alston, Oscar Tshiebwe

Thompson: 6'4", 215 lbs, 44.1 FG%, 28% 3P%, 3.3 STL%
